    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Connection Gap</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Ronald Rettig says small town he lives in has Internet access available through multiple dial-up ISP's as well as DSL and cable modem service</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I reside in Truckee, Calif., a small resort town with a population of about 10,000, high on the eastern slope of the Sierra Nevadas, yet we have Internet access available through multiple dial-up I.S.P.'s as well as D.S.L. and cable modem service. Twenty years ago our little town had no street addresses or stoplights. How times change. Of course, I remember moving to Bronxville, N.Y., in 1954 and being shocked to find the village did not yet have dial phones.</p>
        <p>RONALD RETTIG  Truckee, Calif.</p>
      </block>
